### MCQUIC in the Browser
Max Franke presented [MCQUIC in the browser](https://datatracker.ietf.org/meeting/126/materials/slides-126-mboned-mcquic-in-the-browser-01):
* **Funding & Team**: A German government startup incubator program has funded a team of five people working full-time on multicast QUIC for one year.
* **Architecture**: The design uses a hybrid model. A unicast QUIC connection acts as a security trust anchor. The server coordinates one or more unidirectional Source-Specific Multicast (SSM) channels.
* **Seamless Cutover**: The client initiates playback via unicast immediately (eliminating startup delay) and seamlessly switches to multicast once the multicast path is verified as "green". If the multicast stream fails, it falls back to unicast with negligible interruption.
* **Implementations**:
  * Backend: An extension of Cloudflare's *Quiche* library.
  * Browser: Modified Firefox utilizing the *Necko* QUIC implementation. 
  * Results: Achieved an 80% reduction in egress traffic with only ~60ms of latency overhead for integrity verification. End-to-end stream latency was recorded at around 200ms.
* **Discussion**: Omar Bilal shared alignment with Chrome's direct sockets implementation. Chris Needham (BBC, W3C Media Working Group Chair) offered to collaborate on coordinating API support in browsers. Max pointed to open-source repositories under `github.com/quickcast`.

### Aircast's Internet Multicast Update (post Wimbledon)
Sanjay Patel presented [Aircast's Internet Multicast Update (post Wimbledon)](https://datatracker.ietf.org/meeting/126/materials/slides-126-mboned-aircasts-internet-multicast-update-post-wimbledon-00):
* **System Design**: Focuses on sub-second end-to-end streaming latency using a flow-based model (capturing and sending frames immediately) over multicast and AMT.
* **Deployments**: Described in-venue Wi-Fi and cellular deployments at the US Open (~300-400ms latency), Australian Open, and Wimbledon (~500-800ms latency). 
* **The IPv6 Challenge**: At Wimbledon, the preferred cellular provider operated an IPv6-only network with NAT64. The AMT multicast failed initially because the client could not establish a tunnel with the IPv4-only AMT relay. The team resolved this by hot-fixing the client to reuse the NAT64 address provided during discovery rather than trying to rebuild it.
* **Discussion**: Tim Chown noted long-standing challenges with IPv6 support in VLC AMT. Max Franke mentioned that the new *QuickCast* AMT implementation supports native IPv6 on both the gateway and relay. Omar Bilal noted that his team has written a Linux-based IPv6 relay implementation. Tim Chown expressed interest in deploying Max's relay on the Jisc/GÉANT network.

### Blockcast TreeDN E2E Deployment
Omar Bilal presented [Blockcast TreeDN E2E Deployment](https://datatracker.ietf.org/meeting/126/materials/slides-126-mboned-blockcast-treedn-e2e-deployment-00):
* **Technical Details**: Built an end-to-end multicast-native CDN based on the TreeDN architecture. It relies on PIM joins and leaves to establish state purely on-demand with no static state.
* **DIMT Implementation**: Integrated Dynamic Internet Multicast Tunnels (DIMT) into FRR (Free Range Routing) with Junos upstream interop. Tunnels are built on the first PIM join and torn down on leave.
* **Browser Integration**: Integrated into Chrome Mainline (stable in ~3 months) via the direct sockets API, running under an isolated web app context. 
* **Discussion**: Jeffrey Zhang welcomed the implementation of the DIMT draft and proposed discussing whether to use BGP attributes instead of extended communities to cross AS boundaries more easily. Tim Chown brought up the lack of multicast content on research and education networks. Sanjay Patel volunteered to collaborate on providing live content streams for testing.

### AMT over QUIC
Max Franke presented [AMT over QUIC](https://datatracker.ietf.org/meeting/126/materials/slides-126-mboned-amt-over-quic-00):
* **The Problem**: Packet loss inside an AMT tunnel forces the server to retransmit packets to each client individually (in unicast fallback mode).
* **The Proposal**: Tunneling AMT inside a QUIC connection between the gateway and relay. If a packet is lost in the tunnel, QUIC can retransmit it once over the tunnel rather than wasting egress bandwidth.
* **Additional Benefits**: Inherits QUIC's TLS-based authentication and encryption (securing the tunnel) and supports clean DNS-based discovery.
* **Discussion**: Omar Bilal expressed interest in collaborating on the transport-level reliability and encryption design space. Greg Shepherd and Lenny Giuliano closed by noting the significance of seeing these technologies converge 23 years after the original AMT BOF in Vienna.

